lume offers a unique blend of personal memoirs of “survivors” and their descendants, alongside the work of community activists, public historians, and scholars, all of whom raise questions about how and why in Canada basic civil liberties have been (and, in some cases, continue to be) denied to certain groups in times of perceived national crises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConcentration campszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xEvacuation of civilianszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xEvacuation of civilianszCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aBjorge, Mikhail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaissie, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaissie, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuggy, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDraper, Paula J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdney, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujiwara, Aya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiesbrecht, Jodi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinther, Rhonda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinther, Rhonda L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIacovetta, Franca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKestler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuciuk, Kassandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMandres, Marinel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1